{# ── WHY "NEAR ME" CHANGED · prose. Why proximity used to matter and why cloud accounting
     changed it. Honest, non-disparaging. ── #}
<section class="section section--alt" id="pnm-why">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Why the question changed</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">Why &ldquo;near me&rdquo; used to matter &mdash; and why it doesn&rsquo;t for cloud QuickBooks.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>There was a real reason people searched for a bookkeeper or accountant nearby. Before cloud accounting, the books lived in one place: a desktop file on one machine, a filing cabinet, a shoebox of receipts. Working together meant being in the same room, or couriering a backup file across town. Proximity wasn&rsquo;t a preference &mdash; it was a constraint.</p>
      <p>QuickBooks Online removed that constraint. Your file lives in the cloud, your bank feeds connect directly, your documents attach to transactions, and a Certified ProAdvisor can work inside the exact same file you see &mdash; at the same time, with full audit history. The reconciliation, the cleanup, the month-end close, the migration off Desktop: none of it requires anyone to be physically near your business. It requires someone certified, methodical, and accountable.</p>
      <p>That shift quietly widened your options. When &ldquo;near me&rdquo; was a hard rule, you were limited to whoever happened to set up shop within driving distance &mdash; their specialties, their capacity, their fee structure, take it or leave it. Remove the distance constraint and you can choose the ProAdvisor who actually fits your situation: the one who knows your industry, your QuickBooks version, and your state&rsquo;s tax rules. The best fit for your business may not be the closest one &mdash; and that&rsquo;s an advantage, not a compromise.</p>
      <p>We&rsquo;ll be straight about the flip side. Some owners genuinely work better with someone they can sit across from &mdash; a cash-heavy retail shop that wants a bookkeeper to drop in, an owner who simply prefers handing over a physical box of paperwork. That is a completely valid choice, and remote isn&rsquo;t automatically better for everyone. What we&rsquo;re saying is narrower and honest: for the cloud QuickBooks work we do, distance is no longer what determines quality.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

