{# ── LOCAL TAX · prose. How local tax fluency is handled remotely — routes to the state layer. ── #}
<section class="section section--alt" id="pnm-tax">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">Local where it counts</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">&ldquo;But will a remote firm know my state&rsquo;s taxes?&rdquo;</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>This is the fair objection to a remote firm, and we take it seriously. Sales tax, state filing thresholds, nexus rules, and state-specific quirks are genuinely local &mdash; and getting them wrong is expensive. &ldquo;We serve everyone&rdquo; is meaningless if it means &ldquo;we&rsquo;re shallow everywhere.&rdquo;</p>
      <p>So we&rsquo;re precise about it. We keep your QuickBooks books sales-tax-ready and state-correct for businesses in every state. For the states where we&rsquo;ve done the deepest work, we maintain dedicated pages built around what is actually different there &mdash; the local taxes, the filing realities, the industries. Below, route straight to your state, or tell us where you are if we haven&rsquo;t built your state page yet &mdash; we still serve you remotely.</p>
      <p>One honest boundary: TechBrot does the bookkeeping and operational accounting and keeps your books filing-ready. We do not file income-tax returns and we don&rsquo;t represent you before the IRS &mdash; that is your CPA&rsquo;s or EA&rsquo;s role, and we coordinate directly with them. <a href="/find-an-accountant/">See how we cover every state <span class="lnk-arrow" aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span></a></p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

